  "text": "The results of a meta-analysis of controlled, randomised studies suggest that preference 178 should be given to shorter questionnaires [18] . Shorter questionnaires can be completed more 179 quickly, probably increasing the rate of correct responses [CITATION_1] . Thirdly, CDQ2 includes 180 alcohol consumption, which was not assessed in the FFQ. The effect of alcohol on 181 cardiovascular disease is debated [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . But numerous epidemiologic studies have shown 182 results in support of a protective effect of a small to moderate alcohol consumption and a 183 deleterious effect of a high consumption and/or binge drinking [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Many epidemiologic 184 studies have reported that a small to moderate alcohol consumption can be considered as a 185 favourable lifestyle characteristic. Thus the inclusion of alcohol in a dietary questionnaire is 186 important especially for cardiovascular diseases. It could be criticised that alcohol 187 consumption was not considered in the original FFQ and thus the correlation between the 2 188 questionnaires could be weakened. However this was not the case. completing CDQ2 can be extrapolated to older populations. However, the use of closed 201 answers has facilitated the responses and we can assume this will be the case also for other 202 populations. To date, it has not yet been shown that patients with cardiovascular diseases have 203 an unfavourable GS obtained with CDQ2 whereas it has been reported that a low SDV score 204 (14-item FFQ) is associated with myocardial infarction, PAD and ischemic stroke. There are 205 ongoing studies to check that the CDQ2 global score is as well associated with these diseases. 206",
